# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: webassembly-docs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] This article explains the concepts behind how WebAssembly works including its goals, the problems it solves, and how it runs inside the web browser's JavaScript engine.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] WebAssembly (abbreviated as *Wasm*) is a low-level bytecode format originally designed for the web.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] It is not primarily intended to be written by hand, rather it is designed to be an effective compilation target for source languages like C, C++, Rust, etc.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] This has huge implications for the web platform — it provides a way to run code written in multiple languages on the web at near-native speed, with client apps running on the web that previously couldn't have done so.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] What's more, you don't even have to know how to create WebAssembly code to take advantage of it.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] WebAssembly modules can be imported into a web (or Node.js) app, exposing WebAssembly functions for use via JavaScript.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] JavaScript frameworks could make use of WebAssembly to confer massive performance advantages and new features while still making functionality easily available to web developers.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Historically, the VM has been able to load only JavaScript.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] This has worked well for us as JavaScript is powerful enough to solve most problems people have on the Web today.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] We have run into performance problems, however, when trying to use JavaScript for more intensive use cases like 3D games, Virtual and Augmented Reality, computer vision, image/video editing, and a number of other domains that demand native performance (see WebAssembly use cases for more ideas).
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Additionally, the cost of downloading, parsing, and compiling very large JavaScript applications can be prohibitive.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Mobile and other resource-constrained platforms can further amplify these performance bottlenecks.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] WebAssembly is a different language from JavaScript, but it is not intended as a replacement.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] With the advent of WebAssembly appearing in browsers, the virtual machine that we talked about earlier will now load and run two types of code — JavaScript AND WebAssembly.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] The different code types can call each other as required — the WebAssembly JavaScript API wraps exported WebAssembly code with JavaScript functions that can be called normally, and WebAssembly code can import and synchronously call normal JavaScript functions.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] In fact, the basic unit of WebAssembly code is called a module and WebAssembly modules are symmetric in many ways to ES modules.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] There are several key concepts needed to understand how WebAssembly runs in the browser.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] All of these concepts are reflected 1:1 in the WebAssembly JavaScript API.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] The JavaScript API provides developers with the ability to create modules, memories, tables, and instances.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Given a WebAssembly instance, JavaScript code can synchronously call its exports, which are exposed as normal JavaScript functions.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Arbitrary JavaScript functions can also be synchronously called by WebAssembly code by passing in those JavaScript functions as the imports to a WebAssembly instance.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Since JavaScript has complete control over how WebAssembly code is downloaded, compiled and run, JavaScript developers could even think of WebAssembly as just a JavaScript feature for efficiently generating high-performance functions.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] In the future, WebAssembly modules will be loadable just like ES modules (using `<script type='module'>`), meaning that JavaScript will be able to fetch, compile, and import a WebAssembly module as easily as an ES module.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Above we talked about the raw primitives that WebAssembly adds to the Web platform: a binary format for code and APIs for loading and running this binary code.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Now let's talk about how we can use these primitives in practice.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] The WebAssembly ecosystem is at a nascent stage; more tools will undoubtedly emerge going forward.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Two of the many options for creating Wasm code are an online Wasm assembler or Emscripten.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] These are great resources for people who are trying to figure out where to start, but they lack some of the tooling and optimizations of Emscripten.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] The Emscripten tool is able to take just about any C/C++ source code and compile it into a Wasm module, plus the necessary JavaScript "glue" code for loading and running the module, and an HTML document to display the results of the code.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Emscripten transforms the compiled result of clang+LLVM into a Wasm binary.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] By itself, WebAssembly cannot currently directly access the DOM; it can only call JavaScript, passing in integer and floating point primitive data types.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Thus, to access any Web API, WebAssembly needs to call out to JavaScript, which then makes the Web API call.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Emscripten therefore creates the HTML and JavaScript glue code needed to achieve this.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] The JavaScript glue code is not as simple as you might imagine.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] For a start, Emscripten implements popular C/C++ libraries like SDL, OpenGL, OpenAL, and parts of POSIX.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] These libraries are implemented in terms of Web APIs and thus each one requires some JavaScript glue code to connect WebAssembly to the underlying Web API.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] So part of the glue code is implementing the functionality of each respective library used by the C/C++ code.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] The glue code also contains the logic for calling the above-mentioned WebAssembly JavaScript APIs to fetch, load and run the Wasm file.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] The generated HTML document loads the JavaScript glue file and writes stdout to a `<textarea>`.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] If the application uses OpenGL, the HTML also contains a `<canvas>` element that is used as the rendering target.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] It's very easy to modify the Emscripten output and turn it into whatever web app you require.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] You can find full documentation on Emscripten at emscripten.org, and a guide to implementing the toolchain and compiling your own C/C++ app across to Wasm at Compiling from C/C++ to WebAssembly.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] Do you want to build your own compiler, or your own tools, or make a JavaScript library that generates WebAssembly at runtime?
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] In the same fashion as physical assembly languages, the WebAssembly binary format has a text representation — the two have a 1:1 correspondence.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] You can write or generate this format by hand and then convert it into the binary format with any of several WebAssembly text-to-binary tools.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] For a simple guide on how to do this, see our Converting WebAssembly text format to Wasm article.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] It is also possible to write Rust code and compile over to WebAssembly, thanks to the tireless work of the Rust WebAssembly Working Group.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] You can get started with installing the necessary toolchain, compiling a sample Rust program to a WebAssembly npm package, and using that in a sample web app, over at our Compiling from Rust to WebAssembly article.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] For web developers who want to try WebAssembly without needing to learn the details of C or Rust, staying in the comfort of a familiar language like TypeScript, AssemblyScript will be the best option.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] AssemblyScript compiles a strict variant of TypeScript to WebAssembly, allowing web developers to keep using TypeScript-compatible tooling they are familiar with — such as Prettier, ESLint, VS Code IntelliSense, etc.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] You can check its documentation on https://www.assemblyscript.org/.
[src:webassembly-docs/guides-concepts] This article has given you an explanation of what WebAssembly is, why it is so useful, how it fits into the web, and how you can make use of it.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] To enable WebAssembly to be read and edited by humans, there is a textual representation of the Wasm binary format.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This is an intermediate form designed to be displayed in text editors, browser developer tools, and other similar environments.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This article explains how the text format works in terms of its raw syntax, and how it relates to the underlying bytecode it represents and the wrapper objects that represent Wasm in JavaScript.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] In both the binary and textual formats, the fundamental unit of code in WebAssembly is a module.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] In the text format, a module is represented as one big S-expression.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] S-expressions are an old, simplistic textual format for representing trees; we can therefore think of a module as a tree of nodes that describe the module's structure and its code.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Unlike the Abstract Syntax Tree of a programming language, though, WebAssembly's tree is fairly flat, mostly consisting of lists of instructions.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] First, let's see what an S-expression looks like.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Each node in the tree goes inside a pair of parentheses — `( ... )`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The first label inside the parentheses tells you what type of node it is, and after that, there is a space-separated list of either attributes or child nodes.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] represents a tree with the root node "module" and two child nodes, a "memory" node with the attribute "1" and a "func" node.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] We'll see shortly what these nodes actually mean.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Let's start with the simplest, shortest possible Wasm module.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This module is empty, but it is still a valid module.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Ok, that's not very interesting, let's add some executable code to this module.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This is similar to functions in other languages, although it looks somewhat different.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The signature is a sequence of parameter type declarations followed by a list of return type declarations.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Each parameter has a type explicitly declared; Wasm Number types, Reference types, Vector types.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] After the signature, locals are listed with their type, for example `(local i32)`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Parameters are basically just locals that are initialized with the value of the corresponding argument passed by the caller.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Locals/parameters can be read and written by the body of the function with the `local.get` and `local.set` instructions.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The `local.get`/`local.set` commands refer to the item to be got/set by its numeric index: parameters are referred to first, in order of their declaration, followed by locals in order of their declaration.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The instruction `local.get 0` would get the i32 parameter, `local.get 1` would get the f32 parameter, and `local.get 2` would get the f64 local.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] There is another issue here — using numeric indices to refer to items can be confusing and annoying.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] To mitigate this, you can name parameters, locals, and most other items by including a name prefixed by a dollar symbol (`$`) just before the type declaration.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] And then could write `local.get $p1` instead of `local.get 0`, etc.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Before we write a function body, there is one more important concept to discuss: **stack machines**.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Although the browser compiles it to something more efficient, Wasm execution is defined in terms of a stack machine where the basic idea is that every type of instruction pushes and/or pops a certain number of `i32`/`i64`/`f32`/`f64` values to/from a stack.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] For example, `local.get` is defined to push the value of the local it reads onto the stack, and `i32.add` pops two `i32` values (it implicitly grabs the previous two values pushed onto the stack), computes their sum (modulo 2^32), and pushes the resulting i32 value.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] When a function is called, it starts with an empty stack, which is gradually filled up and emptied as the body's instructions are executed.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The stack contains exactly one `i32` value — the result of the expression (`$p + $p`), which is handled by `i32.add`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The return value of a function is just the final value left on the stack.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The WebAssembly validation rules ensure the stack matches exactly: if you declare a `(result f32)`, then the stack must contain exactly one `f32` at the end.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] If there is no result type, the stack must be empty.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The function body is a list of instructions that are followed as the function is called.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This function takes two parameters, adds them together, and returns the result.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] More things can be put inside function bodies, but we will start with a basic function for now.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] You'll see several more examples as you go along.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] For a full list of the available opcodes, consult the webassembly.org Semantics reference.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Our function won't do very much on its own — now we need to call it.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Like in an ES module, Wasm functions must be explicitly exported by an `export` statement inside the module.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Like locals, functions are identified by an index by default, but for convenience, they can be named.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Here, `add` is the name the function will be identified by in JavaScript, whereas `$add` picks out which WebAssembly function inside the Module is being exported.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] If you want to follow along with the example, save the above our module into a file called `add.wat`, then convert it into a binary file called `add.wasm` using wabt (see Converting WebAssembly text format to Wasm for details).
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Now we've covered the basics, let's look at some more advanced features.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The `call` instruction calls a single function, given its index or name.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] In this example, you'll notice an `(export "getAnswerPlus1")` section, declared just after the `func` statement in the second function — this is a shorthand way of declaring that we want to export this function, and defining the name we want to export it as.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] We have already seen JavaScript calling WebAssembly functions, but what about WebAssembly calling JavaScript functions?
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] WebAssembly doesn't have any built-in knowledge of JavaScript, but it does have a general way to import functions that can accept either JavaScript or Wasm functions.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] WebAssembly has a two-level namespace, so the import statement here imports the `log` function from the `console` module.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] You can also see that the exported `logIt` function calls the imported function using the `call` instruction we introduced above.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Imported functions are just like normal functions: they have a signature that WebAssembly validation checks statically, and they are given an index and can be named and called.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] JavaScript functions have no notion of signature, so any JavaScript function can be passed, regardless of the import's declared signature.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Once a module declares an import, the caller of `WebAssembly.instantiate()` must pass in an import object that has the corresponding properties.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The above import requires an object (let's call it `importObject`) such that `importObject.console.log` is a JavaScript function.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] WebAssembly can create global variable instances, accessible from both JavaScript and importable/exportable across one or more `WebAssembly.Module` instances.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This is very useful, as it allows dynamic linking of multiple modules.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This looks similar to what we've seen before, except that we specify a global value using the keyword `global`, and we also specify the keyword `mut` along with the value's datatype if we want it to be mutable.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The examples above show how to work with numbers in assembly code, adding them to the stack, performing operations on them, and then logging the result by calling a method in JavaScript.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] For working with strings and other more complex data types, we use `memory`, which can be created in either WebAssembly or JavaScript, and shared between environments (more recent versions of WebAssembly can also use Reference types).
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] In WebAssembly, `memory` is just a large contiguous, mutable array of raw bytes that can grow over time (see linear memory in the specification).
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] WebAssembly contains memory instructions like `i32.load` and `i32.store` for reading and writing bytes between the stack and any location in a memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] From JavaScript's point of view, it's as though memory is all inside one big growable `ArrayBuffer`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] JavaScript can create WebAssembly linear memory instances via the `WebAssembly.Memory()` interface and export them to a memory instance, or access a memory instance created within the WebAssembly code and exported.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] JavaScript `Memory` instances have a `buffer` getter, which returns an `ArrayBuffer` that points at the whole linear memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Memory instances can also grow, for example via the `Memory.grow()` method in JavaScript or `memory.grow` in the WebAssembly.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Since `ArrayBuffer` objects can't change size, the current `ArrayBuffer` is detached and a new `ArrayBuffer` is created to point to the newer, bigger memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Note that when you create the memory, you need to define the initial size, and you can optionally specify the maximum size to which the memory can grow.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] WebAssembly will attempt to reserve the maximum size (if specified), and if it is able to do so, it can grow the buffer more efficiently in the future.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Even if it can't allocate the maximum size now, it may still be able to grow later.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The method will only fail if it cannot allocate the *initial* size.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] To demonstrate some of this behavior, let's consider the case where we want to work with a string in our WebAssembly code.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] A string is just a sequence of bytes somewhere inside this linear memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Assuming we've written a suitable string of bytes to WebAssembly memory, we can pass that string to JavaScript by sharing the memory, the offset of the string within the memory, and an indication of its length.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Firstly, let's create some memory and share it between the WebAssembly and JavaScript.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] WebAssembly gives us a lot of flexibility here: we can either create a `Memory` object in JavaScript and have the WebAssembly module import the memory, or we can have the WebAssembly module create the memory and export it to JavaScript.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] For this example, we'll create the memory in JavaScript then import it into WebAssembly.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] First, we create a `Memory` object with 1 page, and add it to our `importObject` under the key `js.mem`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Within our WebAssembly file, we import this memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The memory must be imported using the same two-level key specified in the `importObject` (`js.mem`).
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The `1` indicates that the imported memory must have at least 1 page of memory (WebAssembly currently defines a page to be 64KB).
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Now that we have a shared memory instance, the next step is to write a string of data into it.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] We'll then pass information about where the string is located and its length to the JavaScript (we could alternatively encode the string's length in the string itself, but passing a length is easier for us to implement).
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] First, let's add a string of data to our memory, in this case, "Hi".
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Since we own the entire linear memory, we can just write the string contents into global memory using a `data` section.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Data sections allow a string of bytes to be written at a given offset at instantiation time and are similar to the `.data` sections in native executable formats.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] To share this data with JavaScript, we'll define two functions.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] First, we import a function from JavaScript, which we will use to log the string to the console.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This will need to be mapped to `console.log` in the `importObject` used to instantiate the WebAssembly module.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The function is named `$log` in the WebAssembly and takes `i32` parameters for the string offset and length in the memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The second WebAssembly function, `writeHi()`, calls the imported `$log` function with the offset and length of the string in memory (`0` and `2`).
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This is exported from the module so that it can be called from JavaScript.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Our final WebAssembly module (in text format) looks like this.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] On the JavaScript side, we need to define the logging function, pass it to the WebAssembly, and then call the exported `writeHi()` method.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Note that the logging function `consoleLogString()` is passed to the `importObject` in the property `console.log`, and imported by the WebAssembly module.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The function creates a view on the string in the shared memory using a `Uint8Array` at the passed offset and with the given length.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The bytes are then decoded from UTF-8 into a string using the TextDecoder API (we specify `utf8` here, but many other encodings are supported).
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The string is then logged to console with `console.log()`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The final step is to call the exported `writeHi()` function, which is done after the object is instantiated.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] When you run the code, the console will show the text "Hi".
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] More recent implementations allow you to use multiple memory objects in your WebAssembly and JavaScript, in a way that is compatible with code that is written for implementations that only support a single memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Multiple memories can be useful for separating data that should be treated differently from other application data, such as public vs private data, data that needs to be persisted, and data that needs to be shared between threads.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] It may also be useful for very large applications that need to scale beyond the Wasm 32-bit address space, and for other purposes.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Memories that are made available to the WebAssembly code, either declared directly or imported, are given a zero-indexed, sequentially allocated memory index number.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] All the memory instructions, such as `load` or `store`, can reference any particular memory via its index so you can control which memory you're working with.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The memory instructions have a default index of 0, the index of the first memory added to the WebAssembly instance.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] As a result, if you only add one memory, your code doesn't have to specify the index.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] To explain this in more detail, we'll extend the previous example to write strings to three different memories and log the results.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The code below shows how we first import two memory instances, using the same approach as in the previous example.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] To show how you can create memory within the WebAssembly module, we've created a third memory instance named `$mem2` in the module and *exported* it.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The three memory instances are automatically assigned a memory index based on their order of creation.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The code below shows how we can specify this index (e.g., `(memory 1)`) in the `data` instruction to choose the memory we want to write a string to (you can use the same approach for all other memory instructions, such as `load` and `grow`).
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Here we write a string that indicates each memory type.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Note that the `(memory 0)` is the default, and hence optional.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] To demonstrate this, we write the text `" (Default)"` without specifying the memory index, and this should be appended after `"Memory 0 data"` when the memory contents are logged.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The WebAssembly logging code is similar to the previous example, except that we need to pass the index of the memory that contains the string along with the string offset and length.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The JavaScript code is also very similar to the previous example, except that we create and pass two memory instances to the `importObject()` and the memory exported by the module instance is accessed after it has been instantiated using the resolved promise (`obj.instance.exports`).
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The code to log each string is also a little more complicated because we need to match the memory instance number from the WebAssembly to a particular `Memory` object.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The output of the example should be similar to the text below, except that "Memory 1 data" may have some trailing "rubbish characters", because the text decoder is passed more bytes than are used to encode the string.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] To finish this tour of the WebAssembly text format, let's look at the most intricate and often confusing part of WebAssembly: **tables**.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Tables are basically resizable arrays of references that can be accessed by index from WebAssembly code.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] To see why tables are needed, we need to observe that the `call` instruction we saw earlier (see Calling functions from other functions in the same module) takes a static function index and thus can only ever call one function — but what if the callee is a runtime value?
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] WebAssembly needed a type of call instruction to achieve this, so we gave it `call_indirect`, which takes a dynamic function operand.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The problem is that the only types we can give operands in WebAssembly are (currently) `i32`/`i64`/`f32`/`f64`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] WebAssembly could add an `anyfunc` type ("any" because the type could hold functions of any signature), but unfortunately, this `anyfunc` type couldn't be stored in linear memory for security reasons.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Linear memory exposes the raw contents of stored values as bytes, therefore, Wasm content could arbitrarily observe and corrupt raw function addresses, which is something that cannot be allowed on the web.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The solution was to store function references in a table and pass around table indices instead, which are just i32 values.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] `call_indirect`'s operand can therefore be an i32 index value.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] So, how do we place Wasm functions in our table?
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Moving on, now we've defined the table we need to use it somehow.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] In a higher-level, more expressive language like JavaScript, you could imagine doing the same thing with an array (or probably more likely, an object) containing functions.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The pseudocode would look something like `tbl[i]()`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Since WebAssembly is type-checked, and the `funcref` can potentially have any function signature, we have to supply the presumed signature of the callee at the callsite.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] We therefore include the `$return_i32` type to specify that a function returning an `i32` is expected.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] If the callee doesn't have a matching signature (say an `f32` is returned instead), a `WebAssembly.RuntimeError` is thrown.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] So what links the `call_indirect` to the table we are calling?
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The answer is that there is currently only one table allowed per module instance, and that is what `call_indirect` is implicitly calling.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Because JavaScript has full access to function references, the Table object can be mutated from JavaScript using the `grow()`, `get()` and `set()` methods.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] And WebAssembly code is itself able to manipulate tables using instructions added as part of Reference types, such as `table.get` and `table.set`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Because tables are mutable, they can be used to implement sophisticated load-time and run-time dynamic linking schemes.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] When a program is dynamically linked, multiple instances share the same memory and table.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This is similar to a native application where multiple compiled `.dll`s share a single process's address space.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] To see this in action, we'll create a single import object containing a Memory object and a Table object, and pass this same import object to multiple `instantiate()` calls.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This function creates a constant containing the value `0`, and then uses the `i32.load` command to load the value contained in the provided memory index.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The index provided is `0` — again, it implicitly pops the previous value off the stack.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] So `shared0func` loads and returns the value stored at memory index `0`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] In `shared1.wat`, we export a function called `doIt` — this function creates two constants containing the values `0` and `42`, then calls `i32.store` to store a provided value at a provided index of the imported memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] In the last part of the function, we create a constant with value `0`, then call the function at this index 0 of the table, which is `shared0func`, stored there earlier by the `elem` block in `shared0.wat`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] When called, `shared0func` loads the `42` we stored in memory using the `i32.store` command in `shared1.wat`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Each of the modules that is being compiled can import the same memory and table objects and thus share the same linear memory and table "address space".
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Bulk memory operations are a newer addition to the language.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Seven new built-in operations are provided for bulk memory operations, such as copying and initializing, to allow WebAssembly to model native functions like `memcpy` and `memmove` in a more efficient, performant way.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Another more recent addition to the language is WebAssembly multi-value, meaning that WebAssembly functions can now return multiple values, and instruction sequences can consume and produce multiple stack values.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] At the time of writing (June 2020) this is at an early stage, and the only multi-value instructions available are calls to functions that themselves return multiple values.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] But this will pave the way for more useful instruction types, and other things besides.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] For a useful write-up of progress so far and how this works, see Multi-Value All The Wasm! by Nick Fitzgerald.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] WebAssembly Threads allow WebAssembly Memory objects to be shared across multiple WebAssembly instances running in separate Web Workers, in the same fashion as `SharedArrayBuffer`s in JavaScript.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This enables fast communication between Workers and significant performance gains in web applications.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] The threads proposal has two parts: shared memories and atomic memory accesses.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] As described above, you can create shared WebAssembly `Memory` objects, which can be transferred between Window and Worker contexts using `postMessage()`, in the same fashion as a `SharedArrayBuffer`.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Unlike unshared memories, shared memories must specify a "maximum" size, in both the JavaScript API constructor and Wasm text format.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] Several new Wasm instructions have been added that can be used to implement higher-level features like mutexes, condition variables, etc.
[src:webassembly-docs/understanding-the-text-format] This finishes our high-level tour of the major components of the WebAssembly text format and how they get reflected in the WebAssembly JS API.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:webassembly-docs/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
